{"cursor":"12755","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Single-precision floating-point format' is a computer number format that\noccupies 4 bytes (32 bits) in computer memory and represents a wide dynamic\nrange of values by using a floating point.\n\nIn IEEE 754-2008 the 32-bit base 2 format is officially referred to as\n'binary32'. It was called 'single' in IEEE 754-1985. In older computers, other\nfloating-point formats of 4 bytes were used.\n\nOne of the first programming languages to provide single- and double-precision\nfloating-point data types was Fortran. Before the widespread adoption of IEEE\n754-1985, the representation and properties of the double float data type\ndepended on the computer manufacturer and computer model.\n\nSingle-precision binary floating-point is used due to its wider range over fixed\npoint (of the same bit-width), even if at the cost of precision.\n\nSingle precision is known as 'REAL' in Fortran http://scc.ustc.edu.cn/zlsc/-\nsugon/intel/compiler_f/main_for/lref_for/source_files/rfreals.htm , as\n'float' in C, C++, C#, Java http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/java/nu-\ntsandbolts/datatypes.html and Haskell, and as 'single' in Delphi (Pascal),\nVisual Basic, and MATLAB. However, 'float' in Python, Ruby, PHP, and OCaml and\n'single' in versions of Octave prior to 3.2 refer to double-precision numbers.\n","linknr":191,"url":"Single_precision","recorded":1362477284,"links":19,"instances":["programming_language","programming_language","programming_language","programming_language","programming_language","arithmetic","programming_language"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Binary arithmetic","Computer arithmetic","Data types"],"headings":["IEEE 754 single-precision binary floating-point format: binary32","See also","External links","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Float_example.svg/590px-Float_example.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/1/8/81854e3ec3e7115e1f49dece1c7bbb18.png","//u